{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17610546","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17610546"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:04:31+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:04:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16178"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16178","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16178"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.39,0.05,0.03,0.53,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8869"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74605"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8869","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8869"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16178"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60099"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4937"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7017"},{"type":"tags","id":"7662"},{"type":"tags","id":"8088"},{"type":"tags","id":"8143"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21122"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21124"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74605","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74605"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EInvasive ductal carcinoma is the most common type of breast cancer, accounting for 80% of all breast malignancies. Accurate histological identification is essential for diagnosis and treatment planning.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the typical histological appearance of invasive ductal carcinoma?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Malignant cells forming branching papillary structures","Discohesive cells infiltrating in single-file pattern","Tumour cells floating within pools of mucin","Malignant cells in cords with stromal invasion","Uniform cells arranged in solid expansile sheets"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe characteristic histological appearance of invasive ductal carcinoma shows \u003Cstrong\u003Emalignant cells in cords with stromal invasion\u003C/strong\u003E. These malignant epithelial cells breach the basement membrane and infiltrate the surrounding breast stroma, typically eliciting a desmoplastic response with dense fibrosis. The tumour cells demonstrate nuclear pleomorphism, prominent nucleoli, and increased mitotic activity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options represent other patterns of breast cancer:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMalignant cells forming branching papillary structures\u003C/strong\u003E is characteristic of papillary carcinoma\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUniform cells arranged in solid expansile sheets\u003C/strong\u003E is more typical of medullary carcinoma\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiscohesive cells infiltrating in single-file pattern\u003C/strong\u003E describes the classic appearance of invasive lobular carcinoma\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETumour cells floating within pools of mucin\u003C/strong\u003E is the pattern seen in mucinous (colloid) carcinoma\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe desmoplastic response in invasive ductal carcinoma often creates a firm, stellate mass that can be detected on clinical examination and imaging studies.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Invasive ductal carcinoma shows malignant epithelial cells arranged in cords, nests, and glands that infiltrate through the breast stroma.","Desmoplastic stromal response with dense fibrosis is a characteristic feature of invasive ductal carcinoma.","Nuclear pleomorphism, prominent nucleoli, and increased mitotic activity are key cytological features of invasive ductal carcinoma."],"references":["Scholl AR, Flanagan MB. Educational Case: Invasive Ductal Carcinoma of the Breast. Acad Pathol. 2020 Jan 21;7:2374289519897390. doi: 10.1177/2374289519897390. PMID: 32010760; PMCID: PMC6974746.","Makki J. Diversity of Breast Carcinoma: Histological Subtypes and Clinical Relevance. Clin Med Insights Pathol. 2015 Dec 21;8:23-31. doi: 10.4137/CPath.S31563. PMID: 26740749; PMCID: PMC4689326.","Menon G, Alkabban FM, Ferguson T. Breast Cancer. [Updated 2024 Feb 25]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. [Figure, Invasive Ductal Carcinoma. Histological slide of...] Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK482286/figure/article-18564.image.f9/","Arulkumaran, S., Ledger, W., Denny, L., \u0026 Doumouchtsis, S. (Eds.). (2019). Oxford Textbook of Obstetrics and Gynaecology. Oxford University Press.","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science","Padubidri, V. G., \u0026 Daftary, S. N. (Eds.). (2014). Shaw\u0027s Textbook of Gynecology E-book. Elsevier health sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60099"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16178"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60099","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60099"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-25T19:43:49+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-25T19:44:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8869"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id"